====================================================
WHAT HAPPENS INTERNALLY WHEN WE RUN A JAVA PROGRAM
====================================================

Example:

class Student {

    String name;
    int age;

    static String college = "IIT G";

    public Student(String name, int age){
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
    }

    public void markAttendance(){
        System.out.println(name + " is present");
    }

    public static void changeCollege(String newCollege){
        college = newCollege;
    }
}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args){

        Student s1 = new Student("Aditya", 28);

        s1.markAttendance();

        Student.changeCollege("IIT Bombay");
    }
}

====================================================
STEP 1 : JVM STARTS
====================================================

Command:

java Main

The Operating System starts the JVM process.

JVM creates the runtime memory areas:

1. Heap
2. Method Area
3. Main Thread
4. Main Thread Stack
5. Program Counter (PC Register)

Nothing from our program is executing yet.

====================================================
STEP 2 : CLASS LOADING
====================================================

JVM asks the Class Loader to load Main.class.

Since Main uses Student,

Student.class is also loaded.

The Class Loader stores metadata inside the Method Area.

Method Area now contains:

Class : Main

- Parent = Object
- main(String[])
- Bytecode

Class : Student

Fields

- name
- age
- college (static)

Methods

- Student()
- markAttendance()
- changeCollege()

Notice:

Only the class definitions are loaded.

NO objects are created yet.

====================================================
STEP 3 : STATIC VARIABLES INITIALIZED
====================================================

Static variables belong to the class.

Example:

static String college = "IIT G";

During class initialization,

college is initialized.

Method Area

Student

college -----------> "IIT G"

The String literal "IIT G" is stored in the String Pool
(which is part of Heap).

====================================================
STEP 4 : MAIN THREAD STARTS
====================================================

JVM creates the Main Thread.

Main Thread gets:

- Stack
- Program Counter

A Stack Frame is pushed for main().

Stack

----------------------

main()

args

s1 = null

----------------------

Program Counter points to the first instruction inside main().

====================================================
STEP 5 : EXECUTE

Student s1 = new Student("Aditya", 28);
====================================================

The JVM sees the keyword "new".

It performs the following:

1. Allocates memory in Heap.

Heap

Student Object

name = null
age = 0

2. Calls the constructor.

Student("Aditya",28)

Constructor Stack Frame is pushed.

Stack

Student()

main()

